# AWS Technology                           | History                                                                    | Challenge                                                                                  | How AWS Solved It                                                                                                                                 | Outcome                                                                                                     |
| ---------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Amazon EC2**                           | Launched in **2006** as Amazon's first Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS). | Companies had to purchase expensive physical servers and wait weeks for deployment.        | EC2 introduced virtual servers that can be launched within minutes. Features like AMIs, Security Groups, and Auto Recovery simplified management. | Reduced infrastructure costs, faster deployment, and elastic computing.                                     |
| **Amazon VPC**                           | Introduced in **2009** to provide isolated cloud networking.               | Businesses needed secure, isolated environments similar to traditional data centers.       | AWS introduced Virtual Private Cloud with subnets, route tables, NAT Gateways, Internet Gateways, and Network ACLs.                               | Secure and customizable cloud networking for enterprises.                                                   |
| **Amazon S3**                            | Released in **2006** as scalable object storage.                           | Organizations struggled with scalable, durable, and reliable storage for growing datasets. | S3 provided virtually unlimited object storage with **99.999999999% (11 nines)** durability, versioning, lifecycle policies, and encryption.      | Became one of the world's largest cloud storage services used for backups, data lakes, and static websites. |
| **Amazon EBS**                           | Introduced in **2008** for persistent block storage.                       | EC2 instance storage was temporary and data was lost after termination.                    | EBS introduced persistent storage with snapshots, resizing, encryption, and backup support.                                                       | Reliable storage for databases and enterprise applications.                                                 |
| **Amazon EFS**                           | Released in **2016** as managed network file storage.                      | Sharing files between multiple EC2 instances was difficult.                                | EFS provided scalable shared file storage accessible from multiple Linux instances simultaneously.                                                | Simplified file sharing for web applications and enterprise workloads.                                      |
| **Elastic Load Balancing (ELB)**         | Introduced in **2009**. Later expanded into ALB, NLB, and GWLB.            | Single servers became bottlenecks during high traffic.                                     | ELB automatically distributed traffic across multiple servers and Availability Zones.                                                             | High availability, improved performance, and fault tolerance.                                               |
| **Auto Scaling**                         | Released in **2009**.                                                      | Applications could not handle sudden traffic spikes or wasted resources during low demand. | Auto Scaling automatically launched or terminated EC2 instances based on demand, schedules, or predictions.                                       | Lower infrastructure costs and improved application availability.                                           |
| **Amazon RDS**                           | Introduced in **2009** as managed relational database service.             | Database administration required manual installation, backups, updates, and maintenance.   | AWS automated provisioning, backups, patching, monitoring, replication, and failover.                                                             | Reduced database administration effort while improving reliability.                                         |
| **Amazon CloudWatch**                    | Released in **2009**.                                                      | Administrators lacked centralized monitoring and alerting for cloud resources.             | CloudWatch collected metrics, logs, events, dashboards, and alarms in a centralized service.                                                      | Faster troubleshooting and proactive infrastructure monitoring.                                             |
| **AWS CLI**                              | First released in **2013**.                                                | Managing AWS resources through only the web console was slow and repetitive.               | AWS CLI enabled command-line automation and scripting for all AWS services.                                                                       | Improved automation, scripting, and DevOps workflows.                                                       |
| **Amazon Route 53**                      | Introduced in **2010** as AWS DNS service.                                 | Traditional DNS services had slower failover and limited routing capabilities.             | Route 53 added health checks, latency routing, weighted routing, failover routing, and geolocation routing.                                       | Faster DNS resolution with high availability and intelligent routing.                                       |
| **Amazon CloudFront**                    | Launched in **2008** as AWS CDN.                                           | Users experienced slow website performance due to geographic distance from servers.        | CloudFront cached content at edge locations around the world.                                                                                     | Lower latency, faster content delivery, and improved user experience.                                       |
| **AWS Lambda**                           | Released in **2014**, introducing serverless computing.                    | Organizations spent time managing servers even for small applications.                     | Lambda executed code only when events occurred, without requiring server management.                                                              | Reduced operational overhead and enabled event-driven architectures.                                        |
| **Identity and Access Management (IAM)** | Released in **2011**.                                                      | Sharing the AWS root account created major security risks.                                 | IAM introduced users, groups, roles, and fine-grained permission policies.                                                                        | Secure access control following the principle of least privilege.                                           |



| Topic                    | History                                                                                                                                      | Major Business Challenges                                                                                           | Major Technical Challenges                                                                                                | Solution                                                                                                                                       | Outcome                                                                                                     |
| ------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Git Fundamentals**     | Git was created by **Linus Torvalds in 2005** after the Linux kernel project stopped using the proprietary BitKeeper version control system. | Large development teams struggled with tracking code changes, maintaining versions, and coordinating contributions. | Slow centralized version control systems (CVS, SVN), merge conflicts, accidental overwrites, and limited offline support. | Git introduced a **distributed version control system (DVCS)** with local repositories, fast branching, merging, and complete project history. | Faster development, improved collaboration, reliable version history, and offline development capabilities. |
| **GitHub Collaboration** | **GitHub** was launched in **2008** as a cloud-based Git hosting platform. Microsoft acquired GitHub in **2018**.                            | Open-source projects lacked an easy platform for global collaboration and code sharing.                             | Difficulty reviewing code, managing issues, and coordinating distributed teams.                                           | GitHub introduced **Pull Requests, Code Reviews, Issues, Wikis, Discussions, and GitHub Actions**.                                             | Millions of developers collaborate efficiently on open-source and enterprise projects.                      |
| **GitLab Integration**   | **GitLab** was founded in **2011** by Dmitriy Zaporozhets and Valery Sizov.                                                                  | Companies needed a single platform for source control, CI/CD, security, and deployment.                             | Multiple disconnected tools increased maintenance and integration complexity.                                             | GitLab combined Git repositories with built-in **CI/CD pipelines, issue tracking, DevSecOps, and project management**.                         | Streamlined software delivery with an integrated DevOps platform.                                           |
| **Advanced Git**         | Advanced features such as **Rebase, Cherry-pick, Submodules, Hooks, and Stash** evolved over time to support complex development workflows.  | Managing large enterprise projects with multiple teams and repositories became difficult.                           | Complex branch histories, duplicate commits, dependency management, and enforcing coding standards.                       | Git provided advanced commands for history rewriting, selective commits, reusable repositories, and automated workflows.                       | Cleaner commit history, better repository organization, and improved development productivity.              |
| **IDE Integration**      | Editors like **Visual Studio Code (2015)** added built-in Git integration and extensions.                                                    | Developers constantly switched between command-line tools and editors, reducing productivity.                       | Manual Git commands increased learning curve and development time.                                                        | IDEs integrated Git operations, branch management, merge tools, and extensions into the editor.                                                | Faster development workflow and simplified source control management.                                       |



